+# Independent review request
+
+## Task
+
+Revise `memo.md` (about 400 words) and, if needed, `sensitivity-table.md` in this directory in response to an attached independent review. The review requires: (1) no unsupported claim that crime's 0.251 marginal-mean span is larger than commuting time's 0.237 span; (2) a clear statement that re-referencing cannot alter an attribute's reference-invariant range of level means/max--min AMCE contrast, only an improper ranking of individual reference-coded coefficients; (3) the claim must be limited to the attributes and levels randomized in the experiment; (4) complete multi-level racial-composition sensitivity information, preferably all four marginal means and its invariant range; (5) transparent respondent-clustered uncertainty; (6) no unexplained use of “corrected marginal mean”; and (7) CI style `+0.251 (95% CI [0.168, 0.334])`.
+
+## Existing evidence
+
+The crime levels have measurement-error-corrected marginal means 0.626 (95% CI [0.584, 0.667]) for 20% below and 0.374 (95% CI [0.333, 0.416]) for 20% above the national crime rate. Their contrast is 0.251 (95% CI [0.168, 0.334]). The commuting-time span is 0.237. We will not claim a formal rank because no clustered CI for the difference in spans has been computed.
+
+Racial composition levels are 50% White/50% Nonwhite, 75% White/25% Nonwhite, 90% White/10% Nonwhite, and 96% White/4% Nonwhite. The analysis uses profile-level estimates, applies a reliability correction from a repeated profile task (estimated tau = 0.172), and uses analytical respondent-clustered SEs.
+
+## Proposed response
+
+State that re-referencing changes displayed AMCE coefficients, but not the same underlying level means or their max--min range. For binary crime, the two codings give the same signed contrast in reverse. Present marginal means as primary evidence; call crime large and among the largest observed contrasts, comparable to commuting time, and limit the statement to randomized levels. Update the sensitivity table with the requested racial MM range.
+
+## Question
+
+Is this framing statistically and conceptually correct, and is there anything essential that would still overstate the evidence or fail the reviewer's requested revisions? Give decisive, specific advice only.
